<div id="review_1540775433" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1540775433" />
    <a title="William" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36549125-william"><img alt="William" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593268986p2/36549125.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1540775433?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William" href="/user/show/36549125-william">William</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/10429950-the-fall-of-hyperion">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1540775433" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15831229189418115565"><b>A chaotic mess sprinkled with rubies...</b><br/><br/>(The first book, Hyperion, is a masterpiece)<br/><br/>This continuation of the Hyperion saga seems to have been written by Dan Simmon&apos;s agent, pushing for more pages, using a neural whip on him for more cash. Ugh.<br/><br/>Very long-winded and dull chapters, repetition, clumsy interaction between the pilgrims and other players, religious claptrap flowing endlessly....<br/><br/>Simmons is clearly very (very) literate, hurray. We know that, and his inclusion of endless references to famou</span>
  <span id="freeText15831229189418115565" style="display:none"><b>A chaotic mess sprinkled with rubies...</b><br /><br />(The first book, Hyperion, is a masterpiece)<br /><br />This continuation of the Hyperion saga seems to have been written by Dan Simmon's agent, pushing for more pages, using a neural whip on him for more cash. Ugh.<br /><br />Very long-winded and dull chapters, repetition, clumsy interaction between the pilgrims and other players, religious claptrap flowing endlessly....<br /><br />Simmons is clearly very (very) literate, hurray. We know that, and his inclusion of endless references to famous works and people sadly seem to be only a means to extending the page count, much of the time. (Sometimes, the poetry and references are brilliant, to be fair).<br /><br />And along with all this, some genuine rubies (about half-way through) from the most interesting characters: Sol and Brawne. The Kassad romantic sequences with Moneta are often wonderful, but the battle sequences are tiresomely repetitious.<br /><br />Of the overlong ending, which somehow seems rushed (strange), the stories of Moneta, Sol and Rachel are the most surprising and enjoyable.<br /><br />A good editor would have stripped 150 pages from this book, and enforced a more even pacing and style on Simmons (and his agent).<br /><br />Hyperion was a work of true genius. The Fall of Hyperion is merely a work of commerce.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15831229189418115565" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


