<div id="review_4011009657" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4011009657" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/127815147-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610935970p2/127815147.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4011009657?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/127815147-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4011009657" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2269100134619559239">4.5/5<br/><br/>The first part of this book was a bit of a shock and took me some time to adjust to, which is maybe my own fault for having read this book relatively close to when I had finished “Hyperion”. Not that it starts in a negative way, it was just a contrast to what I had gotten used to in the approach of the previous book. After I settled in with it, “The Fall of Hyperion” turned into an amazing adventure and proved to deliver on every aspect I missed from Simmons with book one. While I am a very</span>
  <span id="freeText2269100134619559239" style="display:none">4.5/5<br /><br />The first part of this book was a bit of a shock and took me some time to adjust to, which is maybe my own fault for having read this book relatively close to when I had finished “Hyperion”. Not that it starts in a negative way, it was just a contrast to what I had gotten used to in the approach of the previous book. After I settled in with it, “The Fall of Hyperion” turned into an amazing adventure and proved to deliver on every aspect I missed from Simmons with book one. While I am a very character-driven reader, which “Hyperion” gave in a way of unique tales, “The Fall of Hyperion” let Simmons shine with his wonderful ability to create a big story, a complex world, and a book full of rich details and nostalgic references that have made me thoroughly enjoy his other works as well. “Hyperion” and “The Fall of Hyperion” are distinct ingredients that combine together to make something epic in prose and storyline. I look forward to seeing what new flavors the Endymion stories will bring to this great mix. It is a series that shows how reliant individual books can be on one another. That may seem like an obvious and typical observation to make when reading a series, but I do think that readers, myself included, will enjoy this specific series much more if they look at it as a whole and not narrow in too much on the critiques of the individual books.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2269100134619559239" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


